Predicting English Premier League Player Performance

An Analysis Using Player-Level Fantasy Data



Figure 1. Hierarchical clustering dendrogram made using half of players with more than 20 games played - 7 clusters.





Figure 2. Hierarchical clustering dendrogram made using half of players with more than 20 games played - 12 clusters.





1) Introduction

In the world of fantasy sports, the goal is always to place first. And the case of fantasy soccer in the Premier League is no exception. The difficulty of this task depends on the skill of other league competitors, the predictability of the sport, and a number of other factors. In order to succeed, it helps to have an awareness of or even expertise in the league. However, since fantasy sports are often more of a hobby than a means of making a living, participants are often irrational and uninformed. With this in mind, I set about constructing a data-driven analysis that might inform a participant’s decisions.

The Fantasy Premier League system run by the Barclays Premier League tracks players and their respective statistics over the course of multiple seasons. These statistics are published on the Premier League’s website, and a github user published a scraped compilation from the 2016-2017 (2016), 2017-2018 (2017), and 2018-2019 (2018) seasons. Therefore, this data is publicly available in csv format. Only the first 12 weeks of the 2018-2019 season are present as this season is in progress.

Each observation in this data set is a player in a game week in a given year. For example, one entry is Mohamed Salah’s statistics for game week one in 2017. In total, there are 52614 observations of player-year-game week combinations. Included in this data set are many basic offensive and defensive statistics for each player as well as match information. Some example player statistics are: minutes played; assists; goals; attempted passes; dribbles; saves; and clearances, blocks, and interceptions. The Fantasy Premier League uses these statistics to assign a player a total number of points earned for each game week. This point total is calculated differently for each position. For example, a goal is worth more when scored by a defender than when scored by a forward. These point totals generally reflect the player’s performance in that game week, with higher points representing a better performance and lower points representing a worse performance.
As a fantasy participant, predicting future total points would be hugely valuable in choosing a team and deciding which players to transfer in or out of one’s team. Thus, using the data set described above, I asked: is it possible to predict a player’s points in the upcoming game week using that player’s statistics from the previous game week? I attempt to answer that question in the following analysis.



2) Methods



Figure 3. First attempt at hierarchical clustering shown in a dendrogram made using mean statistics over all observations for a small selection of popular players.





Figure 4. Second attempt at hierarchical clustering shown in a dendrogram made using mean statistics over all observations for each player.





Figure 5. Third attempt at hierarchical clustering shown in a dendrogram made using mean statistics over weeks with more than zero minutes played for all players other than Joshua Harrop.



The data set described in the introduction presented challenges. Observations were in alphabetical order for each game week in each year. This means that an observation of a certain player was not directly positioned directly below that player’s following game week. At first glance, the ideal setup for the data set would be to have all of the observations for one player grouped in order of date. For example, Aaron Cresswell, the first player alphabetically, would have his most recent game week observation (game week 12 in 2018), then his second most recent game week observation (game week 11 in 2018), and so on. However, with this setup, the last observation for one player would be considered the future observation for the first observation of the next player. For example, the player that alphabetically follows Aaron Cresswell, Aaron Lennon, would have a most recent observation (game week 12 in 2018) which follows Aaron Cresswell’s final observation (game week 1 in 2016). Thus, when statistics from previous weeks would be used to predict the following game week’s total points, Aaron Lennon’s statistics would be predicting Aaron Cresswell’s performance.

One approach to work around this complication would be to make a data set specific to each player, and then create a model for each player. While this a logically simple approach, each model has little value when used with other players. A midfielder like N’Golo Kanté has far a far different statistical profile from a goal keeper like Joe Hart. Thus, using N’Golo Kanté to create a model and then using that model for Joe Hart is pointless.

Another approach is to look at groups of players. In soccer, there are generally 11 positions: goal keeper, left wing defender, right wing defender, left center back, right center back, left wing midfielder, right wing midfielder, center defensive midfielder, left attacking center midfielder, right attacking center midfielder, and forward. These positions may change depending on the layout of positions, or formation, a manager chooses, but this is the most general formation. Considering this, it might be more logical to group all players by position and then form models within each of these groups. These inter-group models can then be used to predict performance for players within these groups. This analysis is more valuable to answering the research question than to create player-specific models, as aforementioned, and the reason is more evident having described the grouping approach. Players with variability in statistics, such as Jamie Vardy, will have noisy, useless models, even when limited to only predicting that player’s performance. Jamie Vardy will likely have trouble repeating his goal scoring streak in the future. So, the average of players who are statistically similar to Jamie Vardy will be better at predicting the future performance of Jamie Vardy than his a model created using his own data.

The two algorithms I used to create these groups were hierarchical clustering and k-means clustering. At first, I solely used hierarchical clustering. To get a sense for how the algorithm would cluster my data, I chose a set of players with which I had some familiarity. The resulting dendrogram is shown in Figure 3. Based on attempted passes, goals conceded, assists, completed passes, dribbles, and fouls, Joe Hart and Petr Cech were grouped together and were more similar to Vincent Kompany, Sergio Agüero, and Romelu Lukaku than they were similar to Lukasz Fabianski. This is despite the fact that Joe Hart, Petr Cech, and Lukasz Fabianski are all goal keepers. This result may have been different with the inclusion of other statistics. Defender Vincent Kompany was more like the goal keepers than the two forwards, Sergio Agüero and Romelu Lukaku. Finally, Eden Hazard was more similar to fellow midfielder N’Golo Kanté than all other players. This initial analysis gave the insight that not all players were grouped according to position.

In the next attempt, I calculated the means of the following variables for each player across all competitions: assists, attempted passes, big chances created, big chances missed, clean sheets, clearances plus blocks plus interceptions, completed passes, creativity, dribbles, errors leading to a goal, fouls, goals conceded, goals scored, offsides, crosses, own goals, penalty saves, red cards, saves, tackles, times tackled, winning goals. Finally, I used these means in the hierarchical and k-means clustering algorithms. The results of the heierarchical clustering algorithm are shown in Figure 4. This dendrogram was very difficult to interpret, but there were some obvious outliers. For example, the player furthest to the bottom of the dendrogram is Joshua Harrop, who played a single game for Manchester United, scored a goal, and has not returned to the Premier League. Figure 5 shows the same dendrogram with Joshua Harrop removed. The dendrogram did not change drastically between figures 4 and 5.

Joshua Harrop served as the motivation to remove players that played fewer than 20 out of 87 possible games, as other outliers often played very few games as well. In addition, all observations where a player did not play in a game were omitted. This left a total of 443 observations of the same mean variables calculated for Figures 4 and 5 where each observation was a player. Using this new data, the two keystone graphics, Figure 1 and Figure 2, were created. In order to fit the names of players on the fan dendrograms, only half of the 443 observations were randomly sampled and used. However, in the formation of models, all 443 players were used including those shown in Figure 1 and Figure 2. Figures 1 and 2 represent dendrogram cuts forming 7 clusters 12 clusters, respectively, with each distinct color representing a separate cluster. These cuts were chosen visually. Again, the data does not require players to be clustered based on position. If this were the case, the algorithm would not cluster Vincent Kompany and Olivier Giroud, a defender and a forward, respectively, together when the dendrogram was cut to a height forming 12 clusters. My visual choice of 7 clusters may interpreted as 6 distinct groups–goal keepers, defenders, wingers, attackers, forwards, keepers, and elite forwards–plus Lewis Dunk. Lewis Dunk was statistically unique because he scored 4 own goals as a defender. I assign each of these groups a label with caution as defenders included players from other positions than defense, for example. In the case of 12 clusters, this could be rationalized as theoretically one cluster for each position, plus Lewis Dunk. However, the principal reasoning for the number of clusters was visual.

In addition to hierarchical clustering, I also used k-means clustering on the same data as used for the hierarchical clustering. For the purpose of comparison to hierarchical clustering, I chose 7 and 12 clusters, as well. I now had a group of 7 clusters made from hierarchical clustering, a group of 12 clusters made from hierarchical clustering, a group of 7 clusters made from k-means clustering, and a group of 12 clusters made from k-means clustering. My total number of clusters was 38.

Finally, I used linear models and the random forest algorithm to predict future points. To do this, I grouped the data used to create clusters by cluster, created the same mean statistics that were used to create clusters but now for the total-cluster mean, ordered the data in descending order of occurrence (i.e. most recent observation first), and lagged these mean statistics. Then, I joined the original vector of mean points back to this lagged data frame as the future points. This allowed me to include the outcome variable, future points, in the same observation as the lagged statistics. For all clusters other than the Lewis Dunk clusters formed in the hierarchical clustering algorithm, I used the 2016 season as training data and the 2017 season and the 12 weeks of the 2018 season as testing data. Lewis Dunk had only played in the 2017 and 2018 season, so I split his data to about half training data and half testing data. Then, I created a linear and a random forest model within each of the 7 clusters made using hierarchical clustering, a linear and a random forest model within each of the 12 clusters made using hierarchical clustering, a linear and a random forest model within each of the 7 clusters made using k-means clustering, and a linear and a random forest model within each of the 12 clusters made using k-means clustering. Again, all models predicted future points using the mean statistics. I did not want to keep all of the mean statistics in my linear models due to my reluctance to over-fit my data. So, I used the step algorithm to determine an optimal linear model according to AIC score for each cluster. Finally, I used my testing data to calculate predictions within each of the 38 clusters, and then calculated a root-mean-square error (RMSE) value for each of the models within those clusters. The 76 RMSE values for all models are presented in Table 1 and Table 2.





3) Results



Table 1. Root-mean-square errors for each model using 7 clusters. Average RMSE values for all clusters (Av(RMSE)) and all clusters except Lewis Dunk (Av(RMSE ND)) for each of the pairings of clustering and modeling algorithms are presented in bold at the bottom of the table.





Table 2. Root-mean-square errors for each model using 12 clusters. Average RMSE values for all clusters (Av(RMSE)) and all clusters except Lewis Dunk (Av(RMSE ND)) for each of the pairings of clustering and modeling algorithms are presented in bold at the bottom of the table.



The main results of this analysis are summarized in Table 1 and Table 2. Again, for a sample of the types of players in each hierarchical clustering cluster, refer to Figure 1 and Figure 2. The average total points earned per game week in the data as a whole was 2.009. This gives a sense as to the size of the errors. The RMSE is supposed to approximate how the model performed in terms of how far off each of the predictions were from the true value. Using this metric, the best approach was to use the random forest algorithm on each of the 7 clusters formed by the k-means algorithm, as shown by the highlighted, enlarged result in Table 1. The next best approach was to use the same technique with 12 clusters instead of 7, as shown by the highlighted result in Table 2. When looking at these results, take caution not to compare the four values in each row. For example, in Table 1, do not compare the linear models in cluster 1 between the two clustering algorithms to draw conclusions about the effectiveness of the clustering algorithms. The players grouped in cluster 1 are different for the hierarchical algorithm and the k-means algorithm. However, it is useful to compare the linear models to the random forest models within each clustering algorithm, as these models used the same data.

Comparing the two regression algorithms within hierarchical clustering for 7 clusters in Table 1, the performance was similar. The average RMSE values for the linear models and the random forests were 1.660 and 1.433, respectively, ignoring Lewis Dunk (cluster 7). Considering that the average points per week was 2.009, these RMSE values are both large. However, for the k-means clustering, the average RMSE value for random forests, 0.325, was about half of that of the linear models, 0.707. The overall average RMSE values for both regression algorithms was lower for k-means than hierarchical clustering. In Table 2, the average RMSE values for 12 clusters are similar to Table 1, with a slight decrease in the advantage of random forests over linear models in the case of k-means clustering and a slight decrease in the advantage of k-means over hierarchical clustering.

Clusters 6 and 7 in the Table 1’s hierarchical columns were identical to clusters 11 and 12 in Table 2’s hierarchical columns for the linear models and were almost identical for the random forest models. This was because the same data was used for each of these clustering-regression combinations. The variation in the random forest RMSE values was due to the randomization in this regression algorithm. The players in clusters 6 and 7 in Table 1 are equivalent to the players clusters 11 and 12 in Table 2. Cluster 6 in Table 1 and cluster 11 in Table 2 represent the so-called “elite forwards”, Harry Kane, Pierre Emerick Aubameyang, Sergio Agüero, and Mohamed Salah. These players are more unpredictable than all other clusters of players, with the exception of Lewis Dunk. It is hard to predict when Lewis Dunk will score an own goal.
In conclusion, between each of the 8 possible combinations of clustering and regression algorithms, the best approach was to create 7 clusters using k-means and then model those clusters using random forests.



4) Conclusion

At the start of this analysis, I asked whether it is possible to predict a player’s points in the upcoming game week using that player’s statistics from the previous game week. Using two clustering algorithms, k-means and hierarchical clustering, and two regression algorithms, linear models and random forest models, I attempted to answer that question. With the data set I used, the best method as measured by RMSE value was 7 models created using random forests, a unique one for each of the 7 clusters formed by k-means clustering. This produced an average RMSE value of 0.325. When compared to 2.009, the average number of points per game week across all data used in the formation of models, this is an encouraging result. This analysis is limited in that it leaves out players who are new to the league, plagued with injuries, or who play infrequently for another reason.

Further analysis migtht consider a number of changes to the current methodology. This analysis could be enhanced with more data from the seasons before 2016. Next, in the first step of clustering, there is an opportunity to experiment with the number of clusters as well as the clustering algorithm. Additionally, the formation of predictive models using these clusters is another place for further testing. I chose to use the 2016 data to form models that were then tested on the 2017 and 2018 data. There could be a better training and testing split. Next, it may be worth trying to predict different outcomes for different clusters. For example, within generally attacking players, it may be worth trying to predict goals instead of overall points. It may also be worth experimenting with other algorithms to form these predictive models. Finally, a nice end result would be to create a shiny app that allows the user to enter a player and his statistics from that week and then calculate his predicted number of points for the following week.

Overall, this analysis can help inform a Fantasy Premier League participant’s decisions about players and team selection. However, it should not be used as a season-long “calculator”. Further, these models will have trouble predicting when a certain player will suddenly have a career-high performance and earn an extreme number of points. It takes a certain amount of luck to earn these points in a fantasy league and distinguish oneself from the competition.
